-16,-3,-24,9,-41,-18,-20,-4,11,-11,-4,-2,-4,-3,-64,-55,-86,-61,-77,-70] In
this chapter we will take a look at Magnus' idea 5.Qd2 in the Anti-Naidorf
with 4. Qxd4. In my opinion this is quite an interesting idea, and the
position is full of possibilities for both sides. I expect many new games in
this line in the future.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {An extremely
popular line after Magnus scored an easy win against Wojtaczek} Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6
({Another direction here is} 5... g6 6. b3 Bh6 $5 {In my opinion a very
interesting idea.} ({Black also tried the normal} 6... Bg7 7. Bb2 Nf6 8. O-O-O
Be6 $146 {A new set-up which didn't work well for Black in the following game}
9. Kb1 Rc8 10. f3 O-O 11. Nge2 Qa5 12. g4 (12. Nf4 $5 {is worthy of
consideration.}) 12... Rfd8 (12... Nd7 13. g5 {is also better for Black.}) 13.
g5 Nh5 {this occured in Nayhebaver,M (2466)-Turqueza,M (2360) Batumi GEO 2018
White should have continued} 14. Nd5 $146 Qxd2 15. Rxd2 $14 {with a solid edge
for White.}) 7. f4 Nf6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. O-O-O a5 {This is how Black develops his
play on the queenside.} 10. a4 Bg4 $5 $146 {An interesting novelty.} ({
Previously Black's main move was} 10... Nb4) 11. Be2 Bxe2 $6 ({Black should
have played} 11... Qb6 12. Kb1 Nb4 $13 {with unclear play.}) 12. Ngxe2 Nb4 13.
Kb1 Rc8 {Studer,N (2484)-Ortiz Suarez,I (2527) Batumi GEO 2018 now} 14. Qe3 $1
{would have secured White an edge.}) 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Kb1 ({
In my opinion more promising for White is} 9. f4 $1 {for example} a6 10. g4 $1
Nxg4 11. Nf3 Nf6 12. Rg1 $36 {with a serious initiaitve on the kingside Xu,X 
(2581)-Liu,Y (2505) Tianjin 2018}) 9... a6 10. f3 b5 11. g4 Nd7 ({Black also
tried the new} 11... Bb7 $146 12. g5 (12. h4 $5 {is worthy of consideration.})
12... Nd7 13. h4 Nc5 14. Nh3 $6 (14. a3 {is a much better move.}) 14... b4 15.
Nd5 $6 ({It's understandable that} 15. Ne2 a5 {didn't appeal to White, still, it was a better choice.}) 15... exd5 16. exd5 {Neiksans,A (2566)-Paiva,D (2206)
Batumi GEO 2018 Black's most precise defense would have been} Ne5 $1 17. f4
Ned7 18. Qxb4 a5 19. Qd4 f6 {and Black's chances are somewhat better.}) 12. h4
$146 ({Before White has only tried} 12. Nge2) 12... Nc5 13. g5 (13. Nce2 $5 {
could be an idea to improve on White's play.}) 13... b4 14. Nce2 a5 15. Nd4
Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Qc7 17. Ne2 e5 $1 {Black easily solved his opening problems and
even got better in the next few moves} 18. Bxc5 dxc5 19. Nc1 Rd8 20. Qe1 Be6
$15 {Sulskis, S (2525)-Lupulescu, C (2606) Batumi GEO 2018 Conclusion: This is a
fresh line which grew in popularity rather quickly. In my opinion, the best
option for Black is 6...g6, after which the arising positions are quite
playable with chances for both sides. In the line with 6...Nf6, White's
strongest reply is 9.f4! with a very promising position.} *

