{[%evp 0,32,16,28,66,44,95,65,78,83,83,36,36,41,20,-2,57,3,15,-8,33,10,136,137,
168,168,147,158,115,115,75,2,77,21,21] Subject of this chapter is the Grand
Prix Attack and the rare move 7...Nd4!?} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7
5. Bb5+ (5. Bc4 {Is White's main alternative here.}) 5... Bd7 6. Bc4 {
provoking bishop to d7 prevents Black from carrying out d6-d5.} Nc6 7. O-O Nd4
$5 {This might be an interesting alternative to Black's two main moves. This
position occured in two games of Grandmaster Denis Kadric.} (7... e6 {and}) (
7... Na5 {are usually played.}) 8. a4 ({The first game featured} 8. Nxd4 cxd4
9. Ne2 Bc6 $1 (9... Qb6 $6 {is hardly a good idea for Black} 10. d3 Nf6 {
Kadric,D (2509)-Georgiev,K (2590) Veliko Gradiste 2018 Now White could have
seized the initiative with} 11. Bb3 O-O 12. f5 $40) 10. d3 d5 $1 11. exd5 Bxd5
12. Bb5+ Kf8 13. Bc4 $146 {A new move which doesn't change the evaluation.} Nh6
14. Ng3 f5 $11 {Black was fine in Kadric,D (2543)-Ziska,H (2550) Batumi 2018})
8... e6 9. Nxd4 (9. d3 Ne7 {is another direction.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nb5 ({
White also has the more positional choice} 10. Ne2 Ne7 11. d3 O-O $13 {with a
complicated game.}) 10... Bc6 11. f5 {Obviously the idea of White's previous
move.} gxf5 $2 {So far Black failed to react well against White's aggressive
play.} (11... a6 $1 $146 {should be critical:} 12. fxe6 f5 $13 {with wild
complications.}) 12. exf5 e5 13. Qh5 d5 14. f6 $1 {A very important resource.}
Bxf6 15. Bb3 $2 {White missed his best chance.} (15. Be2 $1 $146 {with the
following point} a6 16. Rxf6 $1 Nxf6 17. Qxe5+ Qe7 18. Nc7+ Kd8 19. Qxe7+ Kxe7
20. Nxa8 Rxa8 21. b3 $18) 15... d3 16. cxd3 a6 $13 {with unclear play in
Kadric,D (2543)-Mareco,S (2649) Batumi GEO 2018 Conclusion: The move 7. ..Nd4
is absolutely playable and gives Black a chance to fight for the initiative.
The arising positions are extremely sharp and require some deep preparation.
In my notes, I suggest several improvements for Black.} *

