Qxd4 Rd8 {is considered to be absolutely fine for Black.}) 10... Nd5 $5 $146 {
A new and quite natural novelty.} ({Another game featured Black' most popular
move} 10... Qd7 11. a5 Nd5 12. a6 b6 13. d4 cxd4 14. Nxd4 e6 15. Nb5 Bc5 16.
Nd2 ({Black equalized after} 16. Qa4 O-O 17. Rd1 Qc8 18. Nd2 Rd8 19. Nc4 Rd7
20. Be3 Bf8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (36) Poljak,D (2447)-Morozov,D (2425) ICCF email 2015}
) 16... O-O 17. Ne4 Ne5 $6 $146 {Not the best novelty.} ({Much better would
have been} 17... Na5 {, which was played before in the following game} 18. Qa4
Be7 19. c4 Nb4 $13 {with unclear play Betker,J (2448)-Neubauer,R (2421) GER
email 2015}) 18. Qe2 Be7 {Kazhgaleyev,M (2582)-Sutovsky,E (2633) Batumi GEO
2018 White should have continued} 19. Rd1 $1 Qc6 20. b3 Ng6 21. c4 Nf6 22. Nec3
$16 {with a clear positional advantage.}) 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qd7 13. Na3 e6
14. Nc4 Be7 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. Qe2 {Zhigalko,S (2610)
-Nepomniachtchi,I (2768) Batumi 2018 Now Black should have chosen} O-O $146 18.
Re1 Rfd8 {with equal play. Conclusion: At the moment it seems that Black is
winning the battle in the Alapin Variation. In recent games, Black didn't have
any troubles equalizing.} *

