was played.} Bg7 5. Qd2 h6 6. Bf4 g5 (6... c6 {is Black's main alternative.})
7. Be3 $5 {That's why White retreated his bishop to f4 instead of the common
h4.} Ng4 8. Bc4 (8. O-O-O {scores very well for White.}) 8... Nc6 9. Nge2 a6
10. Ng3 Na5 {this is just bad.} (10... h5 $5 {may be a possible improvement.})
11. Be2 Nxe3 12. fxe3 $1 {In general this is White main strategic idea. By
recapturing with the f-pawn he opens the f-file and strengthens the d4-pawn.}
b5 {Yakubboev,N (2521)-Capella,R (1979) Batumi GEO 2018. Now strong would have
been} 13. h4 $1 e6 14. Nh5 Rg8 15. hxg5 Qxg5 16. O-O-O {with a clear advantage.
}) 4... Bg7 5. h4 {I was surprised to discover that this move was not only
played more than 1800 times but also quite often has been the choice of
strong Grandmasters.} h5 (5... c5 {seems to be more promising for Black.}) 6.
Nh3 {White's knight is heading to g5.} Nbd7 7. Ng5 e5 8. dxe5 $5 $146 ({
White refrains from the natural} 8. d5 {which has occurred three times before.})
8... Nxe5 9. Bf4 {It's not easy for Black to create counterplay in the arising
pawn structure.} Qe7 10. Qd2 a6 11. O-O-O Be6 12. Rhe1 O-O 13. Bg3 {White
enjoyed a pleasant edge in Bareev, E (2666)-Pancevski, F (2489) Batumi GEO 2018}
*

